                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Masuri Sukawa wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"><span style="font-style: italic">How you act online is a reflection of you as a person.</span>
<br />

<br />
This is very true.  But I'll go a step further - how you act ALL THE TIME is a reflection of you as a person.  Character is evident in our every action.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It's a fundementally different class of action though. I think what Ravvenn is suggesting is that you cannot expect the behaviors of a person online to match the behaviors of the same person in real life. All of my experiences have led me to believe this is true, and you can't really tell what someone is like by their online persona. So although your actions always reflect our charecter, online only a facet of your charecter comes through. 
<br />

<br />
For example if you're very intelligent, but a slow typer you may be mistaken for someone foriegn, or anti-social, or stupid - all of which may be false. Context matters - the same action can be interpreted in many different ways as well depending on the context. Consider the action of shooting someone, sometimes such an action is justified, and sometimes it isn't, depending on the context.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
Heh, I'm not talking about slow typing.  I'm talking about a person's actions and attitudes toward their fellow gamers.  If you're an asshole to someone in the game, then I can assume one of two things - either you'd act like that in real life or you wouldn't.  If you would, then good.  At least you're genuine.  If you wouldn't, then we have a problem.  Because that means that you're being an asshole to people because you feel shielded by the anonymity of the internet, and that's bad. If you wouldn't say it irl, don't say it online, imo.  If feeling free from repercussions makes you feel like a big dog, take a look at yourself.  Seriously.
<br />

<br />
I hate nothing more than to really, really like someone online then find out that in the real world, they're a completely different person.  It's creepy, because I always wonder - which is the real you?  I avoid those people.
<br />

<br />
This is neither here nor there, I guess, but I just get tired of people explaining away behavior that occurs online as "just a game."  A lot of people use that as a great excuse for being a total ass and thinking it's just a-okay.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
