                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The original posting certainly has brought out a lot of commentary... not necessarily a bad thing.
<br />

<br />
     To address a couple points made above my thoughts:
<br />

<br />
1.  I don't know the man behind Furor.  I am certainly aware of the online persona.  A review of the writings, postings, and the FoH website show someone with a "forceful" viewpoint.  Now whether this agrees with anyone or not be they guildmates, RL friends, the fact that these items constitute a "public" record is beyond dispute.  To that end it is entirely reasonable to judge that material and question the validity of a game company working on a "T for Teen" game hiring that individual.
<br />

<br />
2.  The FoH guildsite is renowned for its flames... the rickshaw... and the public release of IP information to reveal the names of people in some cases obviously wishing to remain anonymous.  This is a public face presented in part by Furor to the rest of the gaming community which obviously extends to the general communities of Everquest and WoW.  Did Blizzard take this into consideration?  
<br />

<br />
     My interest isn't in bashing one individual.  Everyone is entitled to post, rant, and editorialize to their heart's content.  My interest is in the decision making process Blizzard makes in choosing people to assist on a project like WoW.  My interest is in how this and other personel decisions affect the game and the community interest.  In an area where designers change jobs and the internet is abuzz about it, hirings and firings of public figures is fair game for comment.
<br />

<br />
     The action of hiring someone of Furor's reputation (whether you view it positively or negatively) obviously makes a statement whether intentional or not.  The hiring was almost certainly something that was going to be discussed by many different gaming communities.  If Blizzard didn't take into consideration the public nature of the action then they certainly dropped the ball.  I would also like to know why "rumors" have to percolate through the grapevine until confirmed by Blizzard.  Why didn't Furor just post to the FoH site and say "I am working for them now, thanks for your support, can't discuss details."  It would be nice to know so that people reading the FoH fan site as well as Furor's own posts could assess credibility instead of wondering.
<br />

<br />
     I wish Furor the best.  Working on a project like WoW is undoubtably a great oppurtunity.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
